<p><b>Gloow</b> is an experimental arcade game controlled by movement.</p>

<p>Players interact with the game by moving two coloured paddles to steer a set of connected orbs around obstacles. The game is a modern interpretation of the classic ‘wire-loop’ games, in which players have to guide a small metal loop around a complicated route of metal wire without the two metal objects touching.</p>

<p>I wanted to create a game that leans into the physicality of the control scheme</p>

<p>causing players to move with their controllers, as if they were balancing objects on their hands. This invisible link between player and screen adds a physical difficulty to what would otherwise be an easy game.</p>

<p>with a physical controllers</p>

<p>The game is built to allow for both single and multiplayer in the same mode. Multiplayer adds a dimension of communication that makes the game more enjoyable to both watch and play.</p>

<p><b>Gloow</b> was built in <b>OpenFrameworks</b> using OpenCV for computer vision.</p>

